an discourse on the ‘colour question’. It offers a revisionist account of race in science, and provides original studies of the invention of the language of race relations and of resistance to race-thinking led by radical abolitionists and persons of Asian and African descent living in the United Kingdom. The book will be of interest to students and scholars of race, colonialism and culture, and to a readership interested in the history of science and race, anti-slavery and humanitarian movements, and the roots of anti-racist resistance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAsianszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aBlack peoplezGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aMinoritieszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / General.2bisacsh  aanti-slavery.  aculture.  adissent.  aempire.  aknowledge.  amulti-racial.  anature.  arace.  asentiment.  atrusteeship.1 aLorimer, Douglas A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610266940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526102669423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526102669/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles